#Finding the outlier count
# Define a function to count outliers using IQR method
def count_outliers(series):
    Q1 = series.quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = series.quantile(0.75)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
    outliers = (series < lower_bound) | (series > upper_bound)
    return outliers.sum()

#Removing the outliers
def remove_outliers(dataset):
    # Filter only numeric columns
    numeric_cols = df.select_dtypes(include=[np.number]).columns
    numeric_data = df[numeric_cols]

    # Calculate the first and third quartiles (Q1 and Q3)
    Q1 = numeric_data.quantile(0.25)
    Q3 = numeric_data.quantile(0.75)

    # Calculate the interquartile range (IQR)
    IQR = Q3 - Q1

    # Define the lower and upper bounds for outliers
    lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
    upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

    # Identify and remove outliers
    outliers = ((numeric_data < lower_bound) | (numeric_data > upper_bound))
    filtered_df = df[~outliers.any(axis=1)]

    return filtered_df

import pandas as pd
from scipy.stats import f_oneway
from statsmodels.formula.api import ols
from statsmodels.stats.anova import anova_lm

# Assuming ds is your DataFrame
# Convert 'experience_level' and 'employment_type' to categorical variables
ds['experience_level'] = pd.Categorical(ds['experience_level'])
ds['employment_type'] = pd.Categorical(ds['employment_type'])

# Fit the model
model = ols('salary_in_usd ~ experience_level * employment_type', ds).fit()

# Perform two-way ANOVA
anova_results = anova_lm(model)

# Print the results
print(anova_results)

# Extract p-values
p_values = anova_results['PR(>F)']

# Check hypothesis
alpha = 0.05
if any(p_values < alpha):
    print("At least one factor has a significant effect (reject H0)")
else:
    print("None of the factors have a significant effect (fail to reject H0)")

alpha = 0.05  # significance level

# Extracting p-values and F-statistic p-value from the model summary

f_pvalue = result.f_pvalue

# Significance level
significance_level = 0.05

# Checking if null hypotheses are rejected or not
rejected_null_hypotheses = [p < significance_level for p in p_values]

print("\nRejected Null Hypotheses:")
for i, var in enumerate(X.columns):
    print(f"{var}: {'Yes' if rejected_null_hypotheses[i] else 'No'}")

# Checking if the model is significant overall
if f_pvalue < significance_level:
    print("\nThe model is significant overall (p-value < 0.05)")
else:
    print("\nThe model is not significant overall (p-value >= 0.05)")

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Calculate mean salaries based on experience level and company size
salary_based_on_experience = ds['salary_in_usd'].groupby(ds['experience_level']).mean()
salary_based_on_company_size = ds['salary_in_usd'].groupby(ds['company_size']).mean()

plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))
plt.title("Average Salary Based on Experience level and Company size", fontsize=16)

# Creating a boxplot with salary_in_usd on the y-axis, experience_level on the x-axis, and hue as company_size
sns.boxplot(y="salary_in_usd", x='experience_level', data=ds, hue=ds.company_size)

# Adding annotations for mean salaries
for i, exp_level in enumerate(salary_based_on_experience.index):
    plt.text(i, salary_based_on_experience[exp_level], f'Mean: {salary_based_on_experience[exp_level]:.2f}', ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10)

for i, comp_size in enumerate(salary_based_on_company_size.index):
    plt.text(i, salary_based_on_company_size[comp_size], f'Mean: {salary_based_on_company_size[comp_size]:.2f}', ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10)

plt.xlabel("Experience Level", fontsize=16)
plt.ylabel("Salary in USD", fontsize=16)
plt.show()
